{"cursor":"2699","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Training wheels' (also known as 'stabilisers' in the 'UK') are an additional\nwheel or wheels mounted parallel to the rear wheel of a bicycle that assist\nlearners until they have developed a usable sense of balance on the bicycle.\nTypically they are used in teaching very young children to ride a bike, although\nversions for adults exist. The term \"training wheels\" is commonly used in the\nUnited States, Canada and Australia to describe the stabilizers' role in\nlearning to ride bicycles.\n","linknr":161,"url":"Training_wheels","recorded":1362562490,"links":19,"instances":["bicycle_mechanic"],"pdf":["http://www.adventurecycling.org/resources/201102_MechanicalAdvantage_Cornering_Heine.pdf","http://www.adventurecycling.org/resources/201102_MechanicalAdvantage_Cornering_Heine.pdf"],"categories":["Bicycle parts","Wheels"],"headings":["Learning to bicycle","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Training_wheel.jpg/220px-Training_wheel.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Bicycle_diagram-en.svg/150px-Bicycle_diagram-en.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["sheldon_brown","bicycle_mechanic"]],"members":["sheldon_brown"],"related":["Bicycle_wheel","Bicycle","Sense_of_balance","Countersteering","Sheldon_Brown_(bicycle_mechanic)","Balance_bicycle"]}